<P>
   Harry Andrew Blackmun was born Nov. 12, 1908, in Nashville,
Ill., the son of Corwin Manning Blackmun and the former Theo
Reuter. The family moved to the Minneapolis-St. Paul area when he
was a small child.
</P>
<P>
   After high school, the Harvard Club of Minnesota offered
Blackmun a scholarship to Harvard, where he compiled an impressive
academic record. Faced with a close choice between law school and
medical school, he chose Harvard Law School but retained a lifelong
interest in and respect for the medical profession.
</P>
<P>
   He did well in law school, graduating in 1932 and accepting a
federal appeals court clerkship back in Minnesota with an 8th
Circuit judge, John B. Sanborn.
</P>
<P>
   After his clerkship, he taught for a year at a local law school,
the St. Paul College of Law, now known as the William Mitchell
College of Law.
</P>
<P>
   Blackmun then joined a prestigious Minneapolis law firm, Dorsey,
Colman, Barker, Scott &AMP; Barber. He spent 16 years there, working on
tax and estate cases and on the firm's longtime representation of
the Mayo Clinic, the well-known medical research and treatment
center in Rochester, Minn.
</P>
<P>
   In 1950, he left private practice to become general counsel of
the clinic. He spent nearly 10 years in that position, a period he
later said was the happiest in his professional life. The job let
him apply his legal skills to his lifelong interest in medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Blackmun's appointment to the Supreme Court was the result of
political happenstance. He was Nixon's third choice to fill the
vacancy created by the forced resignation of Justice Abe Fortas.
The Senate rejected Nixon's first two choices, Clement F.
Haynsworth Jr., a federal appeals court judge from South Carolina,
and G. Harrold Carswell, a federal district judge from Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate's action frustrated the Nixon administration's plan
to name a Southerner to the court. Nixon then looked north in
search of a noncontroversial nominee who could be easily confirmed
and who at the same time would fit the requirement the president
had set for a ``law and order'' judge.
</P>
<P>
   Burger, whom Nixon had named to the Supreme Court the year
before, suggested his friend Harry Blackmun. Within a month,
Blackmun was confirmed by the Senate by a vote of 94-0. The Supreme
Court seat once occupied by such justices as Oliver Wendell Holmes,
Benjamin N. Cardozo and Felix Frankfurter had been vacant for a
year by the time Blackmun took the oath of office.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting the events that led to his nomination, Blackmun later
referred to himself wryly as ``Old Number Three.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the court, few tourists would have picked Harry Blackmun
out as a justice. He never acquired a trace of self-importance. He
was modest in both his manner and appearance, rarely wearing a suit
to work. He was a good storyteller and excellent mimic, using that
skill to devastating effect in deadpan impersonations of his
colleagues on the court. Trim and sprightly even in advanced age,
he exercised daily in the Supreme Court gym.
</P>
<P>
   Without doubt, nothing else Blackmun ever wrote had as great an
effect or was scrutinized as carefully as his 50-page opinion in
Roe vs. Wade, issued on Jan. 22, 1973.
</P>
<P>
   For the remainder of his career, Blackmun regarded Roe vs. Wade
with pride and a fierce attachment. ``If it goes down the drain,''
he told a group of law students in 1986, ``I'd still like to regard
Roe vs. Wade as a landmark in the progress of the emancipation of
women.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time he retired at the age of 85, Blackmun was the
third-oldest person ever to serve on the court. Only Justice Oliver
Wendell Holmes, who retired at age 90, and Chief Justice Roger B.
Taney, who died in office at 87, were older.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what the numbers are, and it's time,'' Blackmun said as
he stood with Clinton at a White House press conference on April 6,
1994. The president praised him warmly. ``Justice has not only been
his title, it has been his guiding light,'' Clinton said.
</P>
